## Capstone Project: Full VAPT Engagement

#Objective

To simulate a full Vulnerability Assessment and Penetration Testing (VAPT) engagement following the PTES methodology, from reconnaissance to reporting and remediation.

Tools  Used
Kali Linux           – Attacker machine
Metasploit Framework – Exploitation
OpenVAS              – Vulnerability scanning & rescanning
Burp Suite           – API testing
Google Docs          – Reporting

#Engagement Scope

Target: HackTheBox – Lame VM

IP Address: 192.168.1.200

Testing Type: Black‑box internal penetration test

Attack Log (PTES Mapping)
Timestamp	Target IP	Vulnerability	PTES Phase
2025-08-30 14:30:00	192.168.1.200	Open FTP Service	Reconnaissance
2025-08-30 14:45:00	192.168.1.200	VSFTPD 2.3.4 Detected	Enumeration
2025-08-30 15:00:00	192.168.1.200	VSFTPD RCE	Exploitation
2025-08-30 15:10:00	192.168.1.200	Root Shell Access	Post‑Exploitation
Exploitation Summary

The target was running VSFTPD version 2.3.4, which contains a known backdoor vulnerability. Using Metasploit module:

exploit/unix/ftp/vsftpd_234_backdoor


successful remote code execution was achieved, resulting in unauthenticated root access. This confirmed a critical security failure due to outdated services and lack of hardening.

#Remediation & Mitigation

1.Upgrade or remove VSFTPD 2.3.4

2.Disable anonymous FTP access

3.Enforce least privilege on services

4.Apply OS and service patches regularly

5.Implement firewall rules and network segmentation

6.Validate API inputs tested via Burp Suite

7.Conduct periodic vulnerability scans

8.A post‑remediation OpenVAS scan confirmed no remaining critical vulnerabilities.

